{{Politics of Guinea-Bissau}}

The '''Democratic Party of Progress''' ({{lang-pt|Partido Democrático do Progresso}}, PDP) is a political party in [[Guinea-Bissau]].

==History==
The PDP was established on 10 February 1992 by [[Amin Michel Saad]].<ref name=HD>Peter Karibe Mendy (2013) ''Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Guinea-Bissau'', Scarecrow Press, p314</ref> It joined the [[Union for Change]] (UM) alliance prior to the [[Guinea-Bissau general election, 1994|1994 general elections]],<ref name=AED>[http://africanelections.tripod.com/gw.html Elections in Guinea-Bissau] African Elections Database</ref> and Saad became the UM's leader. The UM won six seats in the [[National People's Assembly (Guinea-Bissau)|National People's Assembly]], of which the PDP (though Saad) took one.<ref name=HD/>

The UM was reduced to three seats in the [[Guinea-Bissau general election, 1999–2000|1999–2000 general elections]], and lost them all in the [[Guinea-Bissau legislative election, 2004|2004 parliamentary elections]].<ref name=AED/> It did not nominate a candidate for the presidential elections in [[Guinea-Bissau presidential election, 2005|2005 presidential elections]], and prior to the [[Guinea-Bissau legislative election, 2008|2008 parliamentary elections]] the UM joined the wider [[Alliance of Patriotic Forces]] coalition, which failed to win a seat in the Assembly.

The UM did not contest the [[Guinea-Bissau presidential election, 2009|2009]] or [[Guinea-Bissau presidential election, 2012|2012 presidential elections]], but returned to contest the [[Guinea-Bissau general election, 2014|2014 general elections]], winning one seat in the National People's Assembly.<ref>[http://www.ipu.org/parline-e/reports/2133_E.htm Assembleia Nacional Popular (People's National Assembly)] IPU</ref>

